{
  "query": "How does the evidence for managing existing hedgerows for bats compare to that for planting new ones?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, there is a clear difference in the amount and quality of evidence for managing existing hedgerows versus planting new ones specifically for bat conservation.\n\n**Evidence for managing existing hedgerows for bats:**\nTwo studies evaluated the effects of managing hedges to benefit bat populations, both conducted in the UK. These studies found that hedgerow management can positively affect bat communities, with one replicated site comparison study showing that hedges trimmed \u22653 years prior had more bat species recorded along them than hedges trimmed during the previous winter. The same study found that hedges trimmed \u22653 years prior had higher activity of two of eight bat species/species groups than recently trimmed hedges. However, one replicated paired sites study found that pipistrelle activity did not differ between hedges managed for wildlife on agri-environment scheme farms and hedges on conventional farms.\n\n**Evidence for planting new hedgerows for bats:**\nNo studies have been found that directly evaluated the effects of planting new hedges on bat populations. The systematic searches conducted for these actions found no evidence to assess whether planting new hedgerows is effective or has any harmful impacts on bats.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nThere is moderate evidence supporting the benefits of managing existing hedgerows for bats, with two UK studies demonstrating positive effects on bat species richness and activity levels. In contrast, there is currently no direct evidence available for the effects of planting new hedgerows on bat populations, as no studies have evaluated this specific intervention. This represents a significant knowledge gap in bat conservation research.",
