{
  "query": "How does the evidence for legally protecting bat habitats compare to legally protecting bats during development activities?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence shows distinct differences between legally protecting bat habitats versus legally protecting bats during development activities. For habitat protection (Action ID 2045), five studies provided evidence with measurable population responses: four studies found higher bat abundance or activity in protected versus unprotected areas, with some species showing significantly greater numbers in protected sites. Additionally, 10 out of 11 bat species had distributions that overlapped significantly more than by chance with areas designated to protect them.\n\nIn contrast, legally protecting bats during development activities (Action ID 1935) showed four studies from the UK focusing on licensing requirements. The evidence primarily documented human behavior changes rather than population responses: development licenses for bats more than doubled over three years, but 81% of licensees did not conduct required post-development monitoring. Most concerning, 68% of bat roosts were ultimately destroyed despite licensing requirements, with only 31-67% of compensation roosts being used by bats after development. The action \"Legally protect bat species\" (Action ID 2037) had no studies evaluating its effectiveness.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2045",
    "1935",
    "2037"
  ]
}

